    """JS Fundamentals — var/let/const, Hoisting, Closures, Scope Chain — Key concepts demonstration"""
    print(f"=== JS Fundamentals — var/let/const, Hoisting, Closures, Scope Chain ===")

    # Core data structures
    config: Dict[str, Any] = {
        'topic': 'JS Fundamentals — var/let/const, Hoisting, Closures, Scope Chain',
        'complexity': 'O(n)',
        'space': 'O(1)',
    }
    for k, v in config.items():
        print(f'{k}: {v}')

    # Typical operations
    data = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
    print(f'Input: {data}')
    print(f'Size: {len(data)}')
    print(f'Contains 3: {3 in data}')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    demonstrate()
```

## Session 2: Prototypes & Classes


```mermaid
graph BT
    obj[myObj] -->|__proto__| P[Person.prototype<br/>greet, toString]
    P -->|__proto__| OP[Object.prototype<br/>hasOwnProperty, valueOf]
    OP -->|__proto__| N[null]
    C[Person Constructor] -->|.prototype| P
```


JavaScript's object system is prototype-based. ES6 classes are syntactic sugar over this system — understanding both layers is essential for interviews and debugging.

### The Prototype Chain

Every JavaScript object has an internal `[[Prototype]]` link to another object (or null). When you access a property, JS looks for it on the object itself first, then walks up the chain.

```javascript
const animal = {
  breathe() { return `${this.name} breathes`; }
};

const dog = Object.create(animal);
dog.name = 'Rex';
dog.bark = function() { return 'Woof!'; };

console.log(dog.bark());     // 'Woof!' — own property
console.log(dog.breathe());  // 'Rex breathes' — found on prototype
console.log(Object.getPrototypeOf(dog) === animal); // true

// Check own vs inherited
console.log(dog.hasOwnProperty('bark'));    // true
console.log(dog.hasOwnProperty('breathe')); // false
```

### Constructor Functions (pre-ES6)

```javascript
function Vehicle(make, model) {
  this.make = make;
  this.model = model;
}

Vehicle.prototype.toString = function() {
  return `${this.make} ${this.model}`;
};

function Car(make, model, doors) {
  Vehicle.call(this, make, model); // borrow constructor
  this.doors = doors;
}

Car.prototype = Object.create(Vehicle.prototype);
Car.prototype.constructor = Car;

Car.prototype.describe = function() {
  return `${this.toString()} (${this.doors} doors)`;
};

const civic = new Car('Honda', 'Civic', 4);
console.log(civic.describe());       // 'Honda Civic (4 doors)'
console.log(civic instanceof Car);   // true
console.log(civic instanceof Vehicle); // true
```

### ES6 Classes

```javascript
class Vehicle {
  #vin; // private field (ES2022)

  constructor(make, model) {
    this.make = make;
    this.model = model;
    this.#vin = Math.random().toString(36).slice(2).toUpperCase();
  }

  toString() { return `${this.make} ${this.model}`; }
  getVin() { return this.#vin; }

  static compare(a, b) { return a.make.localeCompare(b.make); }
}

class Car extends Vehicle {
  constructor(make, model, doors) {
    super(make, model); // must call before using 'this'
    this.doors = doors;
  }

  describe() { return `${super.toString()} (${this.doors} doors)`; }
}

const tesla = new Car('Tesla', 'Model 3', 4);
console.log(tesla.describe());     // 'Tesla Model 3 (4 doors)'
console.log(tesla.getVin());       // private field accessible via method
// tesla.#vin — SyntaxError outside the class
```

```typescript
// TypeScript class with access modifiers and generics
abstract class Repository<T extends { id: string }> {
  protected items: Map<string, T> = new Map();

  add(item: T): void { this.items.set(item.id, item); }
  findById(id: string): T | undefined { return this.items.get(id); }
  abstract findAll(): T[];
}

interface User { id: string; name: string; email: string; }

class UserRepository extends Repository<User> {
  findAll(): User[] { return Array.from(this.items.values()); }
  findByEmail(email: string): User | undefined {
    return this.findAll().find(u => u.email === email);
  }
}
```

### The this Keyword — Four Binding Rules

1. **Default**: `this` is `undefined` in strict mode, `globalThis` in sloppy mode.
2. **Implicit**: when called as a method, `this` is the object before the dot.
3. **Explicit**: `call(thisArg, ...args)`, `apply(thisArg, argsArray)`, `bind(thisArg)` set `this`.
4. **new**: when used with `new`, `this` is the newly created object.

```javascript
const user = {
  name: 'Alice',
  greet() { return `Hello, I am ${this.name}`; },
  greetArrow: () => `Hello, I am ${this.name}` // arrow: no own 'this'
};

console.log(user.greet());        // 'Hello, I am Alice' — implicit

const fn = user.greet;
// console.log(fn()); // undefined (strict) or global.name (sloppy)

console.log(fn.call({ name: 'Bob' })); // 'Hello, I am Bob' — explicit

console.log(user.greetArrow());   // 'Hello, I am undefined' — arrow uses outer this

class Timer {
  count = 0;
  start() {
    // Arrow function: 'this' is lexically bound to the Timer instance
    setInterval(() => { this.count++; console.log(this.count); }, 1000);
  }
}
```

### Interview Insight

"What does the `new` keyword do step by step?" — (1) Creates a plain new object. (2) Sets its `[[Prototype]]` to the constructor's `.prototype`. (3) Executes the constructor with `this` bound to the new object. (4) Returns the new object (unless the constructor explicitly returns a different object).

### Python Implementation

